failure require the real LLM?**\n\nReal failures include:\n- LLM generates code with wrong parameter names (because it misunderstood the spec)\n\n\n- LLM generates code with wrong types\n- LLM generates code with wrong return type\n\nThese are fundamentally LLM non-determinism issues — different calls or models produce varying code quality. Mocking the LLM to always produce correct signatures masks the actual failure mode where the LLM generates incorrect ones. I could test the signature extraction logic in isolation (parsing generated strings to verify structure), but that wouldn't catch whether the LLM actually generates the right signature. The real question becomes: am I testing \"does our parsing work given correct code?\" or \"does the LLM generate correct signatures?\"\n\nThe issue description suggests testing that generation produces the right signature, which depends on the LLM. I could use a mock with varied behaviors — correct signatures, wrong parameter names, wrong types — to verify the extraction logic handles diverse cases. This splits into two levels: unit testing validates parsing and validation logic against mocked LLM responses with different failure modes, while agentic testing checks whether the real LLM actually generates correct signatures. Catching production failures requires the real LLM, since a mock that always returns well-formed structures won't expose actual LLM generation failures. The core issue is distinguishing between testing the signature validation logic itself versus catching actual LLM failures. A unit test with mocked LLM outputs could verify the extraction and matching logic works correctly, but wouldn't surface real failures where the LLM generates incorrect signatures. The actual failure mode—LLM producing code that violates the specified interface—inherently requires testing against the real model. So while unit-level signature validation is possible, catching genuine production failures demands agentic-level testing. get