n 0.20 (mock samples could catch some issues), unit 0.05 (isolated parsing), system and workflow each 0.05.\n\nFor the second behavior around generated implementations passing test cases, I need to determine if system level is truly minimal. The generated code needs to execute against actual test cases, which requires more than just mocking—it needs a real execution environment to validate the implementation works correctly. return a function that fails all tests\n- Run the refinement loop up to the attempt limit\n- Assert that after 3 failed attempts, the service stops and returns an error or gives up\n- Verify no fourth attempt is made\n\nPlan consistent: Yes, this tests the loop termination logic with mocked LLM and test execution.\n\nLevel probabilities:\n- Unit: 0.15 (mock LLM failures, verify loop counter)\n- Integration: 0.75 (mock LLM and test execution, run full loop)\n- System: 0.05 (not needed)\n- Agentic: 0.05 (not needed)\n- Workflow: 0.00\n\nSum: 0.15 + 0.75 + 0.05 + 0.05 + 0.00 = 1.00 ✓\n\nI'm seeing a pattern here. Most behaviors need at least Integration level because they involve mocking LLM calls and test execution. A few need System level when actual code execution in a sandbox is required. Agentic testing is useful for validating that real refinement actually improves code quality. The workflow level isn't really needed for these specific behaviors.\n\nFor the final behavior about producing working code for hard functions, I'd run the full pipeline end-to-end with a real LLM and real test execution to verify the refinement process actually converges on working solutions. This would be Workflow level since it exercises the entire system with realistic inputs and validates the core promise of the service. I'm reconsidering whether the minimum level should be Agentic or Integration. The signature matching behavior could be validated at Integration level using mock LLM outputs with intentionally mismatched signatures to verify the extraction logic catches them. However, the real failure mode—where the LLM actually generates an incorrect signature—only surfaces with a real model, making Agentic the true minimum. I'll adjust my assessment to reflect this distinction more clearly. modes for \"signature doesn't match\":\n1. LLM generates code with wrong signature (LLM failure) → requires Agentic\n2. Signature extraction logic is broken (code logic failure) → requires Integration\n3. Signature comparison logic is broken (code logic failure) → requires Integration\n\nFailures 2 and 3 can be caught at Integration level with mock code samples.\nFailure 1 can only be caught at Agentic level.\n\nSo if I want to catch ALL failures, I need Agentic. But the code logic failures (2,3) can be caught at Integration.\n\nFor a comprehensive test plan, you'd have:\n- Integration tests for signature extraction/comparison logic\n- Agentic tests to verify LLM actually generates correct signatures\n\nBut the \"minimum level to catch a real failure\" for behavior 1 could be either:\n- Integration (if the real failure is code logic) or Agentic (if it's LLM generation). The distinction depends on what failure mode I'm most concerned about catching.\n\nGiven this is an LLM-powered service, the actual risk is that the model won't generate correct signatures, making Agentic the appropriate minimum level. I'll adjust the probability distribution to reflect this: Unit 0.05, Integration 0.25, System 0.05, Agentic 0.60, Workflow 0.05.\n\nBehavior 1 requires Agentic testing.\n\nFor behavior 2, I initially thought System was necessary, but I can actually test code execution at Integration level using in-process execution like exec() or eval(). The mock LLM would generate code, I'd run it directly in the test process, and verify the test suite passes or fails. This catches the real failure—generated code not passing tests—without needing subprocess isolation. System level would be safer for untrusted code, but Integration is technically sufficient for the minimum. Subprocess execution is specifically called out as a System-level characteristic, so if the test involves running generated code in a subprocess, that's the minimum level required. For an LLM-powered code generation service, subprocess execution would be essential for safety, making System the appropriate level rather than Integration. I'll finalize my answer as System for behavior 2.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13524,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13524},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"89d71473-918b-4f3d-bbdc-03fe352b15d8","uuid":"d5923f0d-28d7-4307-b212-b85bf5d1c5d8"}
