res, type mismatches, and runtime errors. Additionally, to validate that refinement actually improves code quality, you need real test execution with realistic LLM-generated code (Agentic), not mock implementations.","test_description":"Generate code via the LLM for a target function with a provided test suite. Execute the generated code in a subprocess, running it against each test case. Collect pass/fail results. If tests fail on first attempt, trigger refinement loop and re-execute. Assert that tests eventually pass (by attempt 1, 2, or 3) or that failures are properly captured and reported. Include test cases that are moderately difficult (realistic failure modes), not just trivial cases.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.5,"Agentic":0.2,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When tests fail, failure messages are included in the next LLM prompt for refinement","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This test validates the prompt construction logic — that the system correctly captures test failure output and includes it in the refinement prompt. You can mock both the LLM call and the test execution (return a known failure message) and then intercept/inspect the refinement prompt without needing real LLM calls or real code execution. The failure mode (omitting failure messages) is a straightforward logic bug detectable via integration testing.","test_description":"Mock the LLM to return a code sample that will fail tests (e.g., off-by-one error or missing logic). Mock the test execution to return a specific failure message (e.g., 'AssertionError: expected 5, got 4'). Run the service. Intercept the second LLM call (the refinement prompt) and assert that: (1) the failure message appears verbatim in the prompt, (2) the original code is present for context, and (3) the prompt clearly indicates this is a refinement request.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Service stops after 3 failed attempts and returns structured error with all attempts and results","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This tests the retry-limit logic: ensuring the service doesn't exceed 3 attempts and properly packages results. You can mock the LLM to always generate code that fails tests, then verify the behavior of the retry counter and error response structure. This is a control-flow bug that doesn't require real code execution or real LLM variance — it's detectable via integration-level mocks.","test_description":"Mock the LLM to always return syntactically valid but logically broken code (e.g., always returns 0, missing branching logic). Mock test execution to always fail with a consistent error message. Run the service on a test task. Assert that exactly 3 generation-test cycles occur (no more, no fewer). Verify the final response is a structured error containing: (1) all 3 generated code samples, (2) all 3 test failure outputs, (3) a clear indication that the limit was reached. Assert no 4th generation attempt is made.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.85,"System":0,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Full loop produces working implementation for a function that a single LLM call typically gets wrong","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This is an end-to-end test of the core value proposition: iterative refinement improves code quality. It requires multiple real agentic steps in sequence (generate → test → refine → test → possibly refine again), executed by the real LLM and real test infrastructure. Mocking the LLM would defeat the purpose — you need the real LLM to demonstrate that: (1) it initially fails on hard functions, and (2) refinement actually helps it improve. This is a multi-step agentic workflow that cannot be validated at lower levels.","test_description":"Select a moderately complex function that typically fails on a single LLM attempt (e.g., a tricky parsing algorithm, off-by-one counting problem, or complex conditional logic). Provide natural language description and a test suite. Run the full pipeline with the real LLM: generate code, execute tests, capture failures, refine, execute tests again, repeat up to 3 times. Assert that the code passes all tests by attempt 2 or 3. Run this test 5-10 times to verify it works reliably (accounting for LLM variance). Success metric: at least 80% of runs produce passing code by the 3rd attempt.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.7}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13524,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13524},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"89d71473-918b-4f3d-bbdc-03fe352b15d8","uuid":"26f8bc0e-25b4-474a-aa92-12594950ae09"}
